# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: dudley-observatory
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Armsby founded Albany Medical College in the former Lancaster School at the corner of Lancaster and Eagle Streets in the City of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Albany Hospital was incorporated in 1849 and established two years later on the southwest corner of Dove Street and Lydius Street (now Madison Avenue).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Physicians who taught in the medical school saw patients in the hospital, and students transitioned from lecture halls in the medical school to “shadowing” assignments on the floors of the hospital.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] The hospital, alongside Albany Medical College, established a radio station that took on the call letters *WAMC* in 1958; citing financial burdens, the college/hospital sold the radio station in 1981 to an independent entity, and is the primary member station of NPR for the Albany area.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] In April 2018, the nursing staff voted to unionize and voted to be represented by NYSNA.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] On March 27, 2023, Albany Medical Center went into lockdown after a man entered the hospital with both a BB gun and a shotgun.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] The man, Dino Savocca, 61, was visiting his mother when he barricaded himself in the hospital, triggering a code silver and ordering all patients and staff to shelter in place.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Savocca was apprehended hours later and arraigned the next day on charges of criminal possession of a weapon, kidnapping and menacing.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] While there were no casualties, hospital staff criticized management for not seriously considering proposed safety measures.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] In June 2025, the hospital announced plans for a $25 million emergency department expansion due to the current emergency department having some of the longest wait times in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Albany Medical College (AMC) is a medical school located in Albany, New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] It was founded in 1839 by Alden March and James H.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] Armsby and is one of the oldest medical schools in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-medical-center] The college is part of Albany Medical Center, which includes the Albany Medical Center Hospital.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The oldest city in New York, the City of Albany is the economic and cultural core of New York State's Capital District.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Capital District is a metropolitan area including the nearby cities and suburbs of Colonie, Troy, Schenectady, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] With an estimated 1.3 million residents, the Capital District is one of the most populous metropolitan areas and is the fastest-growing region in Upstate New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The area that ultimately became Albany was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The area was settled by Dutch colonists, who built Fort Nassau in 1614 for fur trading and Fort Orange in 1624.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1664, the English took over the Dutch settlements, renaming the city "Albany" in honor of the Scottish title of the Duke of York (later James II of England and Ireland and James VII of Scotland): the Duke of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city was officially chartered in 1686 under English rule.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It became the capital of New York in 1797 after the formation of the United States.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the oldest surviving settlement of the original British Thirteen Colonies north of Virginia.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th century and throughout most of the 19th, Albany was a center of trade and transportation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city lies toward the north end of the navigable Hudson River.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It was the original eastern terminus of the Erie Canal and was home to some of the earliest railroads in the world.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1920s, a powerful political machine controlled by the Democratic Party emerged in Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's population shrank because of urban sprawl and suburbanization in the latter part of the 20th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1990s, the New York State Legislature approved for the city a US$234 million building and renovation plan, which spurred downtown redevelopment.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2020, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward artificial intelligence, AI-based photonics, quantum computing hardware manufacturing, nanotechnology, and digital electronics.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Hudson River area was originally inhabited by Algonquian-speaking Mohicans, who called it *Pempotowwuthut-Muhhcanneuw*, meaning "the fireplace of the Mohican nation".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Based to the west along the Mohawk River, the Iroquoian-speaking Mohawk called it *skahnéhtati*, also transliterated to Sche-negh-ta-da, "through the pine woods", referring to the path they took there.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] According to Hendrick Aupaumut, the Mohicans came to the area from the north and the west.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] They settled along the Mahicannituck River, which is now called the Hudson River, and called themselves the *Muh-he-con-neok*, the "People of the Waters That Are Never Still".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawks, one of the Five Nations of the Iroquois Confederacy, were based in the Mohawk valley and noted for their fur trading and their access to trade between the Iroquois and other nations.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Mohawk became strong trading partners with the Dutch and English.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It is likely that the area was visited by European fur traders perhaps as early as 1540, but the extent and duration of those visits are unclear.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Permanent European claims began when Englishman Henry Hudson, exploring for the Dutch East India Company on the *Half Moon* (Dutch: *Halve Maen*), reached the area in 1609, claiming it for the United Netherlands.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1614, Hendrick Christiaensen built Fort Nassau on Castle Island (now called Port of Albany), in the Hudson River.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The fort acted as a fur-trading post and was the first documented European structure in present-day Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Commencement of the fur trade provoked hostility from the French colony in Canada and among the natives, all of whom vied to control the trade.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1618, a flood ruined Fort Nassau, but the Dutch replaced it with Fort Orange on the mainland in 1624.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Both forts were named in honor of the leading family of the Dutch Revolt, members of the House of Orange-Nassau.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Fort Orange and the surrounding area were incorporated as the village of Beverwijck (English: Beaverwick or Beaver District) in 1652, and the city of Albany in 1686.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In these early decades of trade, the Dutch, Mohican, and Mohawk developed relations that reflected differences among their three cultures.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is one of the oldest surviving European settlements from the original Thirteen Colonies and the longest continuously chartered city in the United States.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] When New Netherland was captured by the English in 1664, the name was changed from *Beverwijck* to *Albany* in honor of Prince James, Duke of Albany (later King James VII/II).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Duke of Albany was a Scottish title given since 1398, generally to a younger son of the King of Scots.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The name is ultimately derived from *Alba*, the Gaelic name for Scotland.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Dutch briefly regained Albany in August 1673 and renamed the city *Willemstadt*; the English took permanent possession in 1674 with the Treaty of Westminster.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was formally chartered as a municipality by provincial Governor Thomas Dongan on July 22, 1686.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Dongan Charter was virtually identical in content to the charter awarded to the city of New York three months earlier.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Dongan created Albany as a strip of land 1 mile (1.6 km) wide and 16 miles (26 km) long.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Over the years Albany would lose much of the land to the west and annex land to the north and south.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] At this point, Albany had a population of about 500 people.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1754, representatives of seven British North American colonies met in the *Stadt Huys*, Albany's city hall, for the Albany Congress; Benjamin Franklin of Pennsylvania presented the Albany Plan of Union there, which was the first formal proposal to unite the colonies.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Although it was never adopted by Parliament, it was an important precursor to the United States Constitution.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The same year, the French and Indian War, the fourth in a series of wars dating back to 1689, began.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It ended in 1763 with French defeat, resolving a situation that had been a constant threat to Albany and held back its growth.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Tories and prisoners of war were often jailed in the *Stadt Huys* alongside common criminals.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1776, Albany native Philip Livingston signed the Declaration of Independence.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] During and after the Revolutionary War, Albany County saw a great increase in real estate transactions.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] After the 1777 colonial victory at the Battle of Saratoga, the upper Hudson Valley was generally at peace as the war raged on elsewhere.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Prosperity was soon seen all over Upstate New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Migrants from Vermont and Connecticut began flowing in, noting the advantages of living on the Hudson and trading at Albany, while being only a few days' sail from New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany reported a population of 3,498 in the first national census in 1790, an increase of almost 700% since its chartering.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] On November 17, 1793, fire broke out at a stable belonging to Leonard Gansevoort, destroying 26 homes on Broadway, Maiden Lane, James Street, and State Street.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Three were arrested and charged with arson: Pompey, a man belonging to Matthew Visscher; Dinah, a 14-year-old girl belonging to Volkert P.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Douw; and Bet, a 12-year-old girl belonging to Philip S.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] On January 6, 1794, the three were sentenced to death.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Governor George Clinton issued a temporary stay of execution, but Dinah and Bet were executed by hanging on March 14, and Pompey on April 11, 1794.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1797, the state capital was moved permanently to Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] From statehood to this date, the Legislature had frequently moved the state capital between Albany, Kingston, Poughkeepsie, and the city of New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is the tenth-oldest state capital in the United States and the second-oldest city that is a state capital, after Santa Fe, New Mexico.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany has been a center of transportation for much of its history.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the late 18th and early 19th centuries, Albany saw development of the turnpike and by 1815, Albany was the turnpike center of the state.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The development of Simeon De Witt's gridded block system in 1794—which renamed streets that had originally named after the British royal family with names of birds and mammals instead—was intersected by these major arterials coming out of Albany, cutting through the city at unexpected angles.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The construction of the turnpike, in conjunction with canal and railroad systems, made Albany the hub of transportation for pioneers going to Buffalo and the Michigan Territory in the early and mid-19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1807, Robert Fulton initiated a steamboat line from New York City to Albany, the first successful enterprise of its kind anywhere in the world.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] By 1810, with 10,763 people, Albany was the tenth-largest urban place in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The town and village north of Albany known as "the Colonie" was annexed in 1815.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1825 the Erie Canal was completed, forming a continuous water route from the Great Lakes to New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Unlike the current Barge Canal, which ends at nearby Waterford, the original Erie Canal ended at Albany; Lock 1 was north of Colonie Street.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Canal emptied into a 32-acre (13 ha) man-made lagoon called the Albany Basin, which was Albany's main port from 1825 until the Port of Albany-Rensselaer opened in 1932.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1829, while working as a professor at the Albany Academy, Joseph Henry, widely regarded as "the foremost American scientist of the 19th century", built the first electric motor.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Three years later, he discovered electromagnetic self-induction (the SI unit for which is now the henry).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] He went on to be the first Secretary of the Smithsonian Institution.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the 1830 and 1840 censuses, Albany was ranked as the ninth-largest urban place in the nation; it dropped back to tenth in 1850.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] This was the last time the city was one of the top ten largest urban places in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany also has significant history with rail transport, as the location of two major regional railroad headquarters.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Delaware and Hudson Railway was headquartered in Albany at what is now the SUNY System Administration Building.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1853, Erastus Corning, a noted industrialist and Albany's mayor from 1834 to 1837, consolidated ten railroads stretching from Albany to Buffalo into the New York Central Railroad (NYCRR), headquartered in Albany until Cornelius Vanderbilt moved it to New York City in 1867.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] One of the ten companies that formed the NYCRR was the Mohawk and Hudson Railroad, which was the first railroad in the state and the first successful steam railroad running regularly scheduled service in the country.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] While the key to Albany's economic prosperity in the 19th century was transportation, industry and business also played a role.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Largely thanks to the city's Dutch and German roots, beer was one of its biggest commodities.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Beverwyck Brewery, originally known as Quinn and Nolan (Nolan being mayor of Albany 1878–1883), was the last remaining brewer from that time when it closed in 1972.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city's location at the east end of the Erie Canal gave it unparalleled access to both raw products and a captive customer base in the west.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was known for its publishing houses, and to some extent, still is.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany was second only to Boston in the number of books produced for most of the 19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Iron foundries in both the north and south ends of the city attracted thousands of immigrants to the city for industrial jobs.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Intricate wrought-iron details constructed in those years remain visible on what are now historic buildings.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The iron industry waned by the 1890s due to increased costs associated with a newly unionized workforce and the opening of mines in the Mesabi Range in Minnesota.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's other major exports during the 18th and 19th centuries were furs, wheat, meat, and lumber.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] By 1865, there were almost 4,000 saw mills in the Albany area and the Albany Lumber District was the largest lumber market in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city was also home to a number of banks.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Bank of Albany (1792–1861) was the second chartered bank in New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city was the original home of the Albank (founded in 1820 as the Albany Savings Bank), KeyBank (founded in 1825 as the Commercial Bank of Albany), and Norstar Bank (founded as the State Bank of Albany in 1803).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] American Express was founded in Albany in 1850 as an express mail business.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1871, the northwestern portion of Albany—west from Magazine Street—was annexed to the neighboring town of Guilderland after the town of Watervliet refused annexation of the territory.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In return for this loss, portions of Bethlehem and Watervliet were added to Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Part of the land annexed to Guilderland was ceded back to Albany in 1910, setting up the current western border.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The train carrying the body of slain President Abraham Lincoln came through Albany on the way to Illinois and the ghostly image of that train remains.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany opened one of the first commercial airports in the world, and the first municipal airport in the United States, in 1908.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Originally on a polo field on Loudon Road, it moved to Westerlo Island in 1909 and remained there until 1928.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Albany Municipal Airport—jointly owned by the city and county—was moved to its current location in Colonie in 1928.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] By 1916 Albany's northern and southern borders reached their modern courses; Westerlo Island, to the south, became the second-to-last annexation, which occurred in 1926.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Erastus Corning 2nd, arguably Albany's most notable mayor (and great-grandson of the former mayor of the same name), was elected in 1941.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] While Corning brought stability to the office of mayor, it is said even those who admire him greatly cannot come up with a sizable list of "major concrete Corning achievements." Corning is given credit for saving—albeit somewhat unintentionally—much of Albany's historic architecture.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] During the 1950s and 1960s, a time when federal aid for urban renewal was plentiful, Albany did not have growth in its economy or infrastructure.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It lost more than 20 percent of its population during the Corning years, as people moved to newer housing in the suburbs, followed by most of the downtown businesses moving there as well.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] While cities across the country grappled with similar issues, the problems were magnified in Albany: interference from the Democratic political machine hindered progress considerably.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 1960, the mayor sold the city's stake in the airport to the county, citing budget issues.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It was known from then on as Albany County Airport until a massive upgrade and modernization project between 1996 and 1998, when it was rebranded Albany International Airport.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Governor Nelson Rockefeller (1959–1973) (R) tried to stimulate the city with new monumental architecture and large, government-sponsored building projects; he drove construction of the Empire State Plaza, SUNY Albany's uptown campus, and much of the W.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany County Republican Chairman Joseph C.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Frangella once quipped, "Governor Rockefeller was the best mayor Albany ever had." Corning, although opposed to the project, was responsible for negotiating the payment plan for the Empire State Plaza.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Rockefeller did not want to be limited by the Legislature's power of the purse, so Corning devised a plan to have the county pay for the construction and have the state sign a lease-ownership agreement.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The state paid off the bonds until 2004.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It was Rockefeller's only viable option, and he agreed.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the clout Corning gained from the situation, he gained inclusion of the State Museum, a convention center, and a restaurant, back in the plans—ideas which Rockefeller had originally vetoed.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The county gained $35 million in fees and the city received $13 million for lost tax revenue.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Having the state offices in the city enabled it to keep good jobs and retain middle-class residents.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Another major project of the 1960s and 1970s was the construction of Interstate 787 and the South Mall Arterial.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] A proposed Mid-Crosstown Arterial never came to fruition.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] One of the project's main results was separating the city from the Hudson River.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] When Corning died in 1983, Thomas Whalen assumed the mayorship and was reelected twice.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] He encouraged redevelopment of historic structures and helped attract federal dollars earmarked for that purpose.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] What Corning had saved from destruction, Whalen refurbished for continued and new uses.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Mayor's Office of Special Events was created in an effort to increase the number of festivals and artistic events in the city, including a year-long *Dongan Charter* tricentennial celebration in 1986.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Whalen is credited for an "unparalleled cycle of commercial investment and development" in Albany due to his "aggressive business development programs".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Prior to the recession of the 1990s, downtown Albany was home to four Fortune 500 companies.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] After the death of Corning and the retirement of Congressman Sam Stratton, the political environment changed.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Long-term office holders became rare in the 1980s.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Local media began following the drama surrounding county politics (specifically that of the newly created county executive position); the loss of Corning (and eventually the machine) led to a lack of interest in city politics.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The election of Gerald Jennings was a surprise, and he served as mayor from 1994 until his retirement at the end of 2013.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] His tenure essentially ended the political machine that had been in place since the 1920s.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Many state workers were relocated from the Harriman State Office Campus to downtown, helping its retail businesses and vitality.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The first decade of the 21st century saw a real possibility for a long-discussed and controversial Albany Convention Center; it opened in 2017 with the goal of making Albany a viable location for large events hosted by statewide organizations.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany remains an important location for business presence, given its role as de facto seat of Tech Valley and being home to the state capitol.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Fortune 500 companies with offices in Albany include American Express, J.P.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Morgan and Chase, Merrill Lynch, General Electric, Verizon, Goldman Sachs, International Paper, and Key Bank.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany won the All-America City Award in both 1991 and 2009.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] is located at the extreme right of the image.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is about 135 miles (217 km) north of New York City on the Hudson River.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It has a total area of 21.8 square miles (56 km2), of which 21.4 square miles (55 km2) is land and 0.4 square miles (1.0 km2) (1.8%) is water.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The city is bordered on the north by the town of Colonie (along with the village of Menands), on the west by the town of Guilderland, and on the south by the town of Bethlehem.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The former Foxes Creek, Beaver Kill, and Rutten Kill were diverted underground in the 19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] There are four lakes within city limits: Buckingham Lake; Rensselaer Lake at the mouth of the Patroon Creek; Tivoli Lake, which was formed as a reservoir and once connected to the Patroon Creek; and Washington Park Lake, which was formed by damming the Beaver Kill.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The highest natural point in Albany is a USGS benchmark near the Loudonville Reservoir off Birch Hill Road, at 378 feet (115 m) above sea level.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The lowest point is at the Hudson River—which is still technically an estuary at Albany and is affected by the Atlantic tide—at an average of 2 feet (0.61 m) above sea level at low tide and 4 feet (1.2 m) at high tide.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The interior of Albany consists of rolling hills which were once part of the Albany Pine Bush, an area of pitch pine and scrub oak, and has arid, sandy soil that is a remnant of the ancient Lake Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Due to development, the Pine Bush has shrunk from an original 25,000 to 6,000 acres (10,100 to 2,400 ha) today.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] A preserve was set up by the State Legislature in 1988 and is on the city's western edge, spilling into Guilderland and Colonie; it is the only sizable inland pine barrens sand dune ecosystem in the United States, and is home to many endangered species, including the Karner Blue butterfly.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in the humid continental climate zone (Köppen climate classification: Dfa), and features cold, snowy winters, and hot, humid summers; the city experiences four distinct seasons.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is in plant hardiness zone 6a near downtown and along the shore of the Hudson and 5b at its western end.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany receives 40.7 inches (1,030 mm) of precipitation per year, with 138 days of at least 0.01 in (0.25 mm) of precipitation each year.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Snowfall is significant, totaling 59.4 inches (151 cm) per season, but with less accumulation than the lake effect areas to the north and west, as it is farther from Lake Ontario.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] However, Albany is close enough to the Atlantic coast to receive heavy snow from Nor'easters and the city occasionally receives Alberta clippers.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Winters can be very cold with fluctuating conditions; temperatures drop to 0 °F (−18 °C) or below on nine nights per annum.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Summers in Albany can contain stretches of excessive heat and humidity, with temperatures of 90 °F (32 °C) or hotter on nine days per year.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Due to the variety of its communities, Albany is often called a "city of neighborhoods." The neighborhoods of Albany include Arbor Hill; Center Square, "[an] eclectic mix of residential and commercial [buildings], including bars, night clubs, restaurants, and stores"; Pine Hills; and the South End.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Historically, Albany's population has been mixed.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] First dominated by Mohican and Mohawk people, then Dutch and Germans, it was overtaken by the British in the early 19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Irish immigrants soon outnumbered most other ethnicities by the mid-19th century, and were followed by Italians and Poles.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the mid-to-late 20th century, the African-American population increased with thousands of people from the rural South, as part of the Great Migration.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Until after the Revolution, Albany's population consisted mostly of ethnic Dutch descendants.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Settlers migrating from New England tipped the balance toward British ethnicity in the early 19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Jobs on the turnpikes, canals, and railroads attracted floods of Irish immigrants in the early 19th century, especially in the 1840s during the Great Famine, solidifying the city's Irish base.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Michael Nolan became Albany's first Irish Catholic mayor in 1878, two years before Boston.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Polish and Italian immigrants began arriving in Albany in the wave of immigration in the latter part of the 19th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Their numbers were smaller than in many other eastern cities mainly because most had found manufacturing jobs at General Electric in Schenectady.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Jewish community had been established early, with Sephardic Jewish members as part of the Beverwijck community.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Its population rose during the late 19th century, when many Ashkenazi Jews immigrated from eastern Europe.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In that period, there was also an influx of Chinese and east Asian immigrants, who settled in the downtown section of the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Many of their descendants have since moved to suburban areas.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Asian immigration all but halted after the Immigration Act of 1924.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany saw its last large immigration pattern as part of the Great Migration when many African Americans moved there from the American South before and after World War I to fill industrial positions and find other opportunities.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In the early years, African-Americans lived together with Italians, Jews, and other immigrants in the South End, where housing was older and less expensive.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The black community has grown as a proportion of the population since then; African Americans made up three percent of the city's population in 1950, six percent in 1960, 12 percent in 1970, and 30 percent in 2010.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The change in proportion is related mostly to middle-class white families moving to the suburbs and black families remaining within city limits during the same time period.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Since 2007, the number of Burmese refugees to Albany has increased.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Burmese refugee community consists mostly of people of Karen ethnicity.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] An estimated 5,000 Burmese refugees reside in Albany as of January 2015.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Like most cities of comparable age and size, Albany has well-established Orthodox Christian, Roman Catholic, Protestant, and Jewish communities.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to the oldest Christian congregation in Upstate New York and the Mother Churches of two Christian dioceses.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of June 2010, eight churches or religious buildings in the city were listed on the National Register of Historic Places, one of which—St.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Peter's Episcopal Church on State Street—is a National Historic Landmark.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Established in 1642, the congregation of the First Church in Albany (Reformed), also known as the North Dutch Church (on North Pearl Street), is the second-oldest Reformed Church in America.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2023, the city was home to twelve Catholic churches and four Episcopal churches.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Despite its history of Christendom, in 2019 the Albany-Schenectady-Troy MSA was found to be among the most post-Christian cities in the United States in a study by Christian polling firm The Barna Group.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] A significant Jewish presence has existed in Albany as early as 1658.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2010, Albany is home to two Conservative synagogues, a Chabad-Lubavitch synagogue, an Orthodox synagogue, and two Reform synagogues.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is also home to one of the few Karaite synagogues outside Israel.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of 2008, the total membership in Albany's synagogues was estimated at 12,000–13,000, with half the members residing outside the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Since the early 2000s, there has been an increase in Orthodox Jews moving to Albany from the New York Metro area, largely due to cheaper housing prices and closer walking proximity to synagogues.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Islamic community in Albany and its surrounding suburbs is represented by at least four major mosques in the region.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The Muslim population increased substantially starting in the late 2000s, with the arrival of many refugees from countries such as Iraq, Syria, and Afghanistan.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Exact numbers on religious denominations in Albany are not readily available.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Demographic statistics in the United States depend heavily on the United States Census Bureau, which cannot ask about religious affiliation as part of its decennial census.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] It does compile some national and statewide religious statistics, but these are not representative of a city the size of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] One report from 2000 offers religious affiliations for Albany County.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] According to the data, 59.2% of Albany County residents identified as Christian: 47% are Roman Catholic, 8.4% are mainline Protestants, 2.7% are Evangelical Protestants, and 1.1% are Eastern or Oriental Orthodox Christians.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Residents who practice Judaism make up 4.2% of the population and Muslims represent 0.2%.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2020 census, Albany had a population of 99,224.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] 17.8% of residents were under the age of 18 and 13.3% of residents were 65 years of age or older.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females there were 93.5 males, and for every 100 females age 18 and over there were 91.3 males age 18 and over.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] 100.0% of residents lived in urban areas, while 0.0% lived in rural areas.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] There were 42,158 households in Albany, of which 21.8% had children under the age of 18 living in them.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Of all households, 22.4% were married-couple households, 29.1% were households with a male householder and no spouse or partner present, and 39.5% were households with a female householder and no spouse or partner present.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] About 43.0% of all households were made up of individuals and 11.9% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] There were 48,031 housing units, of which 12.2% were vacant.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The homeowner vacancy rate was 2.7% and the rental vacancy rate was 7.8%.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] According to the 2020 American Community Survey, the Latino population was: 4.57% Puerto Rican, 1.45% Dominican, .84% Ecuadorian, .77% Mexican, .69% Salvadoran, .22% Cuban.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2010 census, Albany's population density was 4,572.7 inhabitants per square mile (1,765.5/km2).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] There were 46,362 housing units at an average density of 2,166.4 per square mile (836.5/km2); 5,205 of these units (11.2%) were vacant.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The racial makeup of the city residents was 52.3% white; 27% Black or African American; 0.06% Native American or Native Alaskan; 7.4% Asian; 0.1% Native Hawaiian or Pacific Islander; .06% from other races; and 3.6% from two or more races.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] A total of 9.2% of the population were Hispanic or Latino of any race.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Non-Hispanic Whites were 52.0% of the population in 2010, compared to 87.0% in 1970.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females, there were 90.6 males.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] For every 100 females age 18 and over, there were 86.5 males.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Some 81.3% of the population had completed high school or earned an equivalency diploma.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] As of the 2000 census, the top five ancestry groups in the city were African American (27%), Irish (18.1%), Italian (12.4%), German (10.4%), and English (5.2%); (33.1%) of the population reported "other ancestries".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany is home to a Triqui language-speaking community of Mexican-Americans.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] There were 40,709 households in Albany in 2000, of which 22.0% had children under the age of 18 living with them, 25.3% were married couples living together, 16.1% had a female householder with no husband present, and 54.8% were non-families.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] 41.9% of all households were made up of individuals, and 11.5% had someone living alone who was 65 years of age or older.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The average household size was 2.11 and the average family size was 2.95.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The median income for a household in the city in 2000 was $96,713, and the median income for a family was $100,374 (male, year-round worker) and $91,052 (female, year-round worker).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The per capita income for the city was $73,985.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] About 16.0% of families and 21.7% of the population were below the poverty line, including 28.8% of those under age 18 and 12.5% of those age 65 or over.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The rate of reported violent crimes for 2008 (1,095 incidents per 100,000 residents) were more than double the rate for similarly sized US cities.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Reported property crimes (4,669 incidents per 100,000 residents) were somewhat lower.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] With a 2013 Census-estimated population of 1.1 million, the eight county Capital District, encompassing Albany, Troy, Schenectady and Saratoga, is the third-most populous metropolitan region in the state.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Demographically speaking, the population of Albany and the Capital District mirrors the characteristics of the United States consumer population as a whole better than any other major municipality in the country.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] According to a 2004 study conducted by the Acxiom Corporation, Albany and its environs are the top-ranked standard test market for new business and retail products.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany, Rochester, and Syracuse all scored within the top five.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's violent crime rate was 10.03 per 1,000 residents in 2023, compared to 7.69 in Buffalo, 7.39 in Rochester, 8.22 in Syracuse, and 7.72 in New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] New York State had statewide violent crime rate of 3.90 per 1,000 people in 2023.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's economy, along with that of the Capital District in general, is heavily dependent on government, health care, education, and more recently, technology.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Because of these typically steady economic bases, the local economy has been relatively immune to national economic recessions in the past.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 2009, more than 25 percent of the city's population worked in government-related positions.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Albany's estimated daytime population is more than 162,000.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Companies based in Albany include Trans World Entertainment, AMRI Global and Clough Harbour.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] In 2019, Albany had the fourth-highest amount of lawyers in its employment pool (7.5 lawyers per 1,000 jobs) compared to the rest of the nation, behind Washington, D.C., Trenton, New Jersey, and New York City, respectively.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Since the 2000s, the economy of Albany and the surrounding Capital District has been directed toward high technology, a growing fourth sector of the area's economic base.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] Tech Valley is a marketing name for the eastern part of New York State, encompassing Albany, the Capital District, and the Hudson Valley.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] The area's high technology ecosystem is supported by technologically focused academic institutions including Rensselaer Polytechnic Institute and the State University of New York Polytechnic Institute.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p01] A notable video game development cluster has grown in and around Albany starting in the 2010s.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's geographic situation—roughly equidistant from New York City to the south and Montreal to the north—makes it a convenient stop for nationally touring artists and acts.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Palace Theatre and The Egg are mid-sized forums for music, theater, and spoken-word performances; the Capital Repertory Theatre is smaller.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The MVP Arena is the city's largest musical venue for nationally and internationally prominent bands.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] It also hosts trade shows, sporting events, and other large gatherings.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In recent years, the city's government has invested resources to cultivate venues and neighborhoods that attract after-hours business.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Madison Avenue, Pearl Street, Delaware Avenue and Lark Street are the most active entertainment areas in the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Many restaurants, clubs, and bars have opened since the mid-1990s, revitalizing areas that had once been abandoned and reclaiming old row houses, businesses, and a pump station.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Much of the bar restaurant scene features classic Irish Pubs.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Price Chopper Fabulous Fourth and Fireworks Festival at the Empire State Plaza celebrates Independence Day with musical performances and the region's largest fireworks display.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Chefs' Food & Wine Festival donates all net proceeds to deserving Albany Arts Organizations and is held the Thursday-Saturday preceding Martin Luther King Weekend.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Because of Albany's historical and political significance, the city has numerous museums, historical buildings, and historic districts.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to the New York State Museum, the New York State Library and the New York State Archives; all three facilities are in the Cultural Education Center at the south end of Empire State Plaza and are free to the public.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The USS *Slater* (DE-766), a decommissioned World War II destroyer escort that was restored in 1998, is a museum ship docked in the Hudson River at Quay Street.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] It is the only ship of its kind still afloat.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Heritage Area Visitors Center, at the corner of Clinton Avenue and Broadway at Quackenbush Square, hosts a museum, gift shop, and the Henry Hudson Planetarium.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In early 2012, the Irish American Heritage Museum opened in downtown Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The museum is home to exhibits highlighting the contributions of the Irish people in America.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is home to 57 listings on the National Register of Historic Places (NRHP) and five National Historic Landmarks.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Ten Broeck Mansion, a 1797 Federal-style mansion (later renovated in the Greek-Revival style) built for Abraham Ten Broeck (mayor of Albany 1779–1783 and 1796–1798) is a historic house museum and the headquarters of the Albany County Historical Association; it was added to the NRHP in 1971.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Later known as "Arbor Hill", it gave the current neighborhood its name.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has been the subject, inspiration, or location for many written and cinematic works.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Many non-fiction works have been written on the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] One of the city's more notable claims to fame is *Ironweed* (1983), the 1984 Pulitzer Prize-winning book by Albany native William Kennedy.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] *Ironweed* was the third in a series of books by Kennedy known as the "Albany Cycle".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The elusive author Trevanian also grew up in Albany and wrote *The Crazyladies of Pearl Street* (2005), about a North Albany neighborhood along Pearl Street.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The book is considered a semi-autobiographical memoir.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 1987, the film version of *Ironweed* premiered at the Palace Theatre.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The movie starred Jack Nicholson and Meryl Streep, each of whom were nominated for Academy Awards for their performances; much of the filming was done on location in Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Most recently the downtown area was the site of filming for the action-thriller *Salt*, starring Angelina Jolie, and the action-comedy *The Other Guys*, starring Will Ferrell and Mark Wahlberg.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Authors Herman Melville and Henry James lived with their families in Albany when young, before their careers.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] James identified his character Isabel Archer, the heroine of his novel *The Portrait of a Lady*, as being from Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Gregory Maguire, author of *Wicked: The Life and Times of the Wicked Witch of the West* (adapted for the Broadway hit *Wicked*), grew up in North Albany and graduated from SUNY Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Empire State Plaza, a collection of state agency office buildings, dominates almost any view of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Built between 1965 and 1978 at the hand of Governor Nelson A.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Rockefeller and architect Wallace Harrison, the complex is a powerful example of late American modern architecture and remains a controversial building project both for displacing city residents and for its architectural style.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The most recognizable aspect of the complex is the Erastus Corning Tower, the tallest building in New York outside of New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Juxtaposed at the north end of the Plaza is the 19th-century New York State Capitol, the seat of the New York State Legislature and the home of the Governor's office.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's initial architecture incorporated many Dutch influences, followed soon after by those of the English.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Quackenbush House, a Dutch Colonial brick mansion, was built c.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] 1736; Schuyler Mansion, a Georgian-style mansion, was built in 1765; and the oldest building in Albany is the 1728 Van Ostrande-Radliff House at 48 Hudson Avenue.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's housing varies greatly, with mostly row houses in the older sections of town, closer to the river.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Housing type quickly changes as one travels westward, beginning with two-family homes of the late 19th century, and one-family homes built after World War II in the western end of the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall, designed by Henry Hobson Richardson, was opened in 1883.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Capitol was opened in 1899 (after 32 years of construction) at a cost of $25 million, making it the most expensive government building at the time.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's Union Station, a major Beaux-Arts design, was under construction at the same time; it opened in 1900.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 1912, the Beaux-Arts styled New York State Department of Education Building opened on Washington Avenue near the Capitol.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] It has a classical exterior, which features a block-long white marble colonnade.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The 1920s brought the Art Deco movement, which is illustrated by the Home Savings Bank Building (1927) on North Pearl Street and the Alfred E.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Smith Building (1930) on South Swan Street, two of Albany's tallest high-rises.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Architecture from the 1960s and 1970s is well represented in the city, especially at the W.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman State Office Building Campus (1950s and 1960s) and on the uptown campus of the University at Albany (1962–1971).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The state office campus was planned in the 1950s by governor W.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Averell Harriman to offer more parking and easier access for state employees.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The uptown SUNY campus was built in the 1960s under Governor Rockefeller on the site of the city-owned Albany Country Club.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Straying from the popular open campus layout, SUNY Albany has a centralized building layout with administrative and classroom buildings at center surrounded by four student housing towers.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The design called for much use of concrete and glass, and the style has slender, round-topped columns and pillars reminiscent of those at Lincoln Center in New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Downtown has seen a revival in recent decades, often considered to have begun with Norstar Bank's renovation of the former Union Station as its corporate headquarters in 1986.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Knickerbocker Arena (MVP Arena) was originally slated for suburban Colonie, but was instead built downtown and opened in 1990.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has teams in two top-level professional sports leagues in the United States and Canada (New York Atlas, and Albany Firebirds), and several minor-league sports teams with varying levels of support.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils were a minor league ice hockey team that moved to the city for the 2010–11 season.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] They played in the American Hockey League and were affiliated with the New Jersey Devils of the National Hockey League.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Devils replaced the Albany River Rats, who played in the Capital Region from 1990 to 2010, when they relocated to Charlotte, North Carolina.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Devils moved to Binghamton, New York in 2017.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Times Union Center has previously hosted arena football teams including the Albany Firebirds in the Arena Football League (AFL) from 1990 to 2000 and then a team originally known as the Albany Conquest and later the Firebirds in the af2, the AFL's developmental league, from 2002 to 2009.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Empire played in the AFL from 2018 through the 2019 season when the league folded.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] A new Albany Empire was relaunched in the National Arena League for the 2021 season.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, Antonio Brown bought the team; after a series of problems with payments and personnel, the NAL suspended the franchise in the middle of the 2023 season.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] A relaunched Albany Firebirds franchise began playing in 2024.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Tri-City ValleyCats short season minor league baseball team have played at the Joseph L.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Bruno Stadium on the Hudson Valley Community College campus in North Greenbush since 2002.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to the ValleyCats' arrival, the Albany-Colonie Diamond Dogs (1995–2002) played at Heritage Park in Colonie; due to financial pressures, and facing impending competition from the ValleyCats, the franchise folded in 2002.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Legends (International Basketball League), played in the Washington Avenue Armory from 2010 to 2014 before moving to Schenectady.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Patroons have played at the Armory on and off since 1982 and currently play in The Basketball League.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] With the large number of local colleges and universities around Albany, college sports are popular.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The University at Albany's Great Danes play at the Division I level in all sports.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The football team is a member of the Coastal Athletic Association while all other sports teams play as members of the America East Conference.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2006, UAlbany became the first SUNY-affiliated school to send a team to the NCAA Division I men's basketball tournament.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Siena Saints saw a rise in popularity after their men's basketball team made it to the NCAA Tournament in 2008, 2009, and 2010.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] All 18 Saints teams are Division I and play in the Metro Atlantic Athletic Conference.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Although Siena's campus is in nearby Colonie, the men's basketball team plays at the Times Union Center.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] UAlbany hosted the New York Giants training camp from 1996 to 2012.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] On February 23, 2021, it was announced that the National Lacrosse League (NLL) would return to the city with the relocation of the New England Black Wolves.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The team was named the Albany FireWolves on April 15, 2021.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] This is the second NLL team to be based in the area; the first, the Albany Attack, played in the city from 2000 to 2003.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2023, the Premier Lacrosse League (PLL) selected cities for their 8 franchises, and Albany was chosen as the primary home for the New York Atlas.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2024, the Albany Firebirds began playing in the AFL at the MVP Arena.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] After one season in the AFL, the team moved to the AF1.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The 518 Ballers (American Basketball Association) have played at Our Savior's Christian School since 2023.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has more than 60 public parks and recreation areas.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was organized as the Middle Public Square in 1806.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Its current location has been public property since the *Dongan Charter* of 1686 gave the city title to all property not privately owned.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park was designed by John Bogart and John Cuyler in 1870, and opened for public use the following year.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The original lake house, designed by Frederick W.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The park had previously been used as a cemetery; its graves were moved to Albany Rural Cemetery.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Washington Park is a popular place to exercise and play sports; skate during the winter; people-watch during Tulip Fest; and attend plays at the amphitheater during the summer.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Other parks in Albany include Lincoln Park, Buckingham Park, the Corning Preserve, the Albany Skyway and the Pine Bush.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Lincoln Park, southwest of the Empire State Plaza, was organized in 1886 and was originally known as Beaver Park.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Today, the park has a pool that is open during the summer months.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Buckingham Lake Park is between Manning Boulevard and Route 85 in the Buckingham Pond neighborhood; it contains a pond with fountains, a footpath, a playground, and picnic tables.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Riverfront Park at the Corning Preserve has an 800-seat amphitheatre that hosts events in non-winter months, most notably the *Alive at 5* summer concert series.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Preserve's visitors center details the ecology of the Hudson River and the local environment.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The park has a bike trail and boat launch and was effectively separated from downtown by Interstate 787 until the opening of the Hudson River Way in 2002.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Other public parks include Westland Hill Park, Hoffman Park, Beverwyck Park, and Liberty Park, today a small circular grassy patch in downtown on Hudson Avenue, which is Albany's oldest park.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Ridgefield Park is home to the clay courts of the Albany Tennis Club, one of the oldest tennis clubs in the United States.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The municipal golf course, New Course at Albany, was constructed in 1929 as the Albany Municipal Golf Course, later renamed the Capital Hills at Albany, and remodeled in 1991.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany has a strong mayor-council government, which functions under the Dongan Charter, granted by colonial governor Thomas Dongan in 1686 when Albany was incorporated.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] A revised charter was adopted by referendum in 1998, but was legally reckoned as an amendment to the Dongan Charter.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] This gives Albany the distinction of having the oldest active city charter in the United States and "arguably the longest-running instrument of municipal government in the Western Hemisphere." The mayor, who is elected every four years, heads the executive branch of city government.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The current mayor, Kathy Sheehan, was first elected in 2013.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Common Council represents the legislative branch of city government and is made up of fifteen council members (each elected from one ward) and an at-large Common Council President.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The current president is Corey Ellis; he began his term in January 2018.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] While Albany has its own city government, it has also been the seat of Albany County since the county's formation in 1683 and the capital of New York since 1797.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] As such, the city is home to all branches of the county and state governments, as well as its own.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany City Hall sits on Eagle Street, opposite the State Capitol, and the Albany County Office Building is on State Street.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The state government has offices scattered throughout the city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is in the 20th Congressional district, represented by Paul Tonko (D) in the United States House of Representatives.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The city is represented by Chuck Schumer (D) and Kirsten Gillibrand (D) in the United States Senate.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] On the state level, the city is in the 44th district in the New York Senate, represented by Patricia Fahy (D).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In the New York Assembly, western Albany is in the 109th district, represented by Gabriella Romero (D) while downtown and eastern Albany are in the 108th district, represented by John T.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] As the seat of Albany County, the city is the location of the county's courts including Family Court, County Court, Surrogate Court, Supreme Court, and New York Court of Appeals.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany is the site of a federal courthouse that houses the United States District Court for the Northern District of New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's politics have been dominated by the Democratic Party since the 1920s; Daniel (Uncle Dan) O'Connell established a political machine in the city with the election of William Stormont Hackett as mayor in 1922.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Prior to that, William Barnes Jr. had set up a Republican machine in the 1890s.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Barnes' success is attributed to the fact that he owned two newspapers in Albany and that he was the grandson of Thurlow Weed, the influential newspaper publisher and political boss.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] O'Connell's organization overcame Barnes' in 1922 and survived well into the 1980s (even after his death).
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In many instances, votes were outright bought.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Gerald Jennings' upset in the 1993 Democratic mayoral primary over Harold Joyce, who had the Democratic Party's formal endorsement and had only recently been its county chairman, is often cited as the end of the O'Connell era in Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In the early 21st century, Albany continued to be dominated by the Democratic Party.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Democratic Party enrollment in the city was 38,862 in 2009, while Republican enrollment was 3,487.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2022, every elected city position had been held by a Democrat since 1931.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In November 2013, Kathy Sheehan became the first woman to be elected Mayor of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The City School District of Albany (CSDA) operates the city's public school system, which consists of 17 schools and learning centers; in addition, there are 7 charter schools, including Green Tech Charter High School, and Albany Leadership High School.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In the 2015–2016 school year, over 9,000 students were enrolled in the public school system.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The district had an average class size of 18, an 81-percent graduation rate, and a 5-percent dropout rate.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Although considered by the state to be one of the lowest-achieving high schools in New York, Albany High was listed as the nation's 976th best high school in a 2010 *Newsweek/Washington Post* report.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany also has a number of private schools, including the coed Bishop Maginn High School and Albany Free School; the all-boys Albany Academy; and the all-girls Academy of the Holy Names and Albany Academy for Girls.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany Medical College (private), today part of Albany Medical Center, was founded in 1839.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany Law School (private) is the oldest law school in New York and the fourth-oldest in the country; it was opened in 1851.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] President William McKinley was an alumnus.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences (private) is the second-oldest pharmacy school in New York and the fifteenth-oldest in the United States.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Normal School, one of the oldest teachers colleges in the United States, opened in 1844; it was later known as the State Teachers College.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] It eventually evolved into the University at Albany, also known as SUNY Albany (public), which inherited the Normal School's original downtown campus on Western Avenue.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The center of the campus moved to its current Uptown Campus in the west end of the city in 1970.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] SUNY Albany is a unit of the State University of New York and one of only four university centers in the system.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Other colleges and universities in Albany include Empire State College, The College of Saint Rose, Excelsior College, Maria College, Mildred Elley, and Sage College of Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Nearby Hudson Valley Community College (HVCC) fills the community college niche in the Albany-Troy area.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The effect of the campuses on the city's population is substantial: Combining the student bodies of all the aforementioned campuses (except HVCC) results in 63,149 students, or almost 70 percent of the 2008 estimate of Albany's permanent population.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The *Times Union* is Albany's primary daily newspaper and the only one based close to the city; its headquarters moved from within city limits to suburban Colonie in the 1960s after a dispute with Mayor Corning over land needed for expansion.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Its circulation totals about 73,000 on weekdays and 143,000 on Sundays.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Serving Albany to a lesser degree are *The Daily Gazette*, based in Schenectady, and *The Record*, of Troy.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] *Metroland* is the alternative newsweekly in the area, publishing each Thursday, while *The Business Review* is a business weekly published each Friday.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The *Legislative Gazette*, another weekly newspaper, focuses exclusively on issues related to the Legislature and the state government.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] As of 2010, the Albany-Schenectady-Troy media market is the 63rd-largest in the country in terms of radio and the 57th-largest in terms of television audiences.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] It is a broadcast market with historical significance.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The pioneering influence of General Electric in Schenectady directly contributed to the area emerging as the birthplace of station-based television with WRGB; the station was also the first affiliate of NBC.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 1947, the region was home to the first independently owned and operated commercial FM radio station in the United States: W47A.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] WGY was the second commercial radio station in New York and the twelfth in the nation.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District is home to ABC affiliate WTEN 10, CBS affiliate WRGB 6 (also operating CW affiliate WCWN 45), Fox affiliate WXXA 23, NBC affiliate WNYT 13 (also operating MyNetworkTV affiliate WNYA 51), and PBS member station WMHT 17.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Charter Communications hosts Spectrum News Capital Region, the area's only local 24-hour news channel.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Thruway is the most prominent highway serving Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] From Albany westward, it is part of Interstate 90, connecting Albany with major cities such as Syracuse, Rochester and Buffalo.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] To the south, it becomes part of Interstate 87 and leads to New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] A short un-tolled section of Interstate 90 extends around the northern and eastern portions of Albany before linking back up with the Berkshire extension of the Thruway, which leads to the Massachusetts Turnpike and ultimately to Boston.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] North of Albany, Interstate 87 follows the Northway to Canada at Champlain; Autoroute 15 continues into Quebec, linking Albany to Montreal.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Interstate 787 links downtown Albany to the southbound I-87/Thruway to the south, while to the north, it links with the free portion of Interstate 90 before continuing to Troy, Watervliet, Colonie, and Menands.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] By way of Route 7, I-787 connects to the Northway.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Since the closure of Union Station on Broadway, area passenger-rail service is provided by Amtrak at the Albany-Rensselaer station across the river in Rensselaer.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2009, the station saw more than 720,000 passengers, making it Amtrak's second-busiest in New York, behind Manhattan's Penn Station.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Amtrak provides service south to New York City; north to Montreal, and Burlington (Vermont); west to Niagara Falls, Toronto and Chicago; and east to Boston.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany's major airport is Albany International Airport in Colonie.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Major airline service to Albany includes service by: American Airlines, Delta Air Lines, Southwest Airlines, JetBlue Airways, and United Airlines; Million Air is the local fixed-base operator.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] In 2010, Albany had the highest average airfare in New York, though the per-mile cost on its busiest routes was second-lowest in the state.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The Capital District Transportation Authority (CDTA) provides bus service throughout Albany and the surrounding area, including Schenectady, Troy, and Saratoga Springs.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The city was once served by an urban streetcar service maintained by the United Traction Company.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] As in many American cities, after the advent of the automobile, light rail services declined in Albany and were replaced by bus and taxi services.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Greyhound Lines, Trailways, Peter Pan, Short Line, Vermont Translines, and Yankee Trails buses all serve a downtown terminal.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Low-cost curbside bus service from the SUNY Albany campus and the Rensselaer station is also provided by Megabus, with direct service to New York City.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Albany, long an important Hudson River port, today serves domestic and international ships and barges through the Port of Albany-Rensselaer, on both sides of the river.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The port has the largest mobile harbor crane in the state of New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The New York State Barge Canal, the ultimate successor of the Erie Canal, is in use today, largely by tourist and private boats.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] The city of Nijmegen, Netherlands connected with Albany following World War II.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] With the help of the Catholic university in Albany, the Catholic University of Nijmegen (Radboud University Nijmegen) rebuilt its partly destroyed library, with over 50,000 books being donated to the Dutch university.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] To show its gratitude for post-war assistance, the city sent Albany 50,000 tulip bulbs in 1948; this act led to the establishment of the annual Tulip Festival.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-new-york-p02] Most of the other connections were made in the 1980s during Mayor Whalen's term in office as part of his cultural expansion program.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The **Albany Regency** was a group of politicians who controlled the New York state government between 1822 and 1838.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Originally called the **"Holy Alliance"**, it was instituted by Martin Van Buren, who remained its dominating spirit for many years.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The group was among the first American political machines.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] In the beginning they were the leading figures of the Bucktails faction of the Democratic-Republican Party, later the Jacksonian Democrats, and finally the Hunkers faction of the Democratic Party.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The Albany Regency was a loosely organized group of politicians with similar views and goals who resided in or near Albany, New York, the state capital.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] They controlled the nominating conventions and patronage of their party within New York State, and by dictating its general policy, exerted a powerful influence in national as well as state politics.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] They derived their power largely from their personal influence and political sagacity, and were, for the most part, earnest opponents of political corruption, though they uniformly acted upon the principle, first formulated in 1833 by one of their number (William L.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The Regency developed party discipline and originated the control of party conventions through officeholders and others subservient to it.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The spoils system they had created would dominate late-19th-century American politics, but in the beginning, observed the technical qualifications of the candidates for office they nominated.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Thurlow Weed, who coined the name "Albany Regency", wrote he "had never known a body of men who possessed so much power and used it so well".
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] However, this also may have been intended by Weed to be a disparaging remark.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The leading figure of the Albany Regency was Martin Van Buren.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Upon Van Buren's election to the United States Senate in 1821, several of his friends and aides, including Benjamin F.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Flagg, took over the day-to-day management of the political organization that had been developed under Van Buren.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Roger Skinner, state printer Edwin Croswell, Benjamin Knower, John Adams Dix, and Charles E.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Dudley also became members of the Regency.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Their organ was the *Argus* newspaper of Albany, founded in 1813 by Jesse Buel (1778–1839) and edited from 1824 to 1854 by Edwin Croswell.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The Regency was powerful enough during this era that it largely dictated policy to New York City's Tammany Hall, which served as the Democratic organization of that city.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The Regency ended when Marcy was defeated in the election for Governor of New York by the opposing Whig's candidate William H.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Seward in 1838, which led to a radical change in state politics.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] Also cited as a factor is a bitter factional split in 1848 (see Barnburners) which gave the other party the patronage the Regency used to use against it.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] The Regency was reduced in a few years to unorganized individuals.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] In 1845 Mackenzie published private letters between Jesse Hoyt and various members of the Albany Regency.
[src:dudley-observatory/albany-regency] These letters described negotiations between various members of the Regency for financial transactions and appointments to government office and exposed how members of the Regency were able to profit from speculatory notes and political corruption.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the oldest natural sciences.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The early civilizations in recorded history made methodical observations of the night sky.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] These include the Egyptians, Babylonians, Greeks, Indians, Chinese, Maya, and many ancient indigenous peoples of the Americas.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the past, astronomy included disciplines as diverse as astrometry, celestial navigation, observational astronomy, and the making of calendars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the few sciences in which amateurs play an active role.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] This is especially true for the discovery and observation of transient events.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Amateur astronomers have helped with many important discoveries, such as finding new comets.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] "Astronomy" and "astrophysics" are broadly synonymous in modern usage.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Sometimes, as in the introduction of the introductory textbook *The Physical Universe* by Frank Shu, "astronomy" means the qualitative study of the subject, whereas "astrophysics" is the physics-oriented version of the subject.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Some fields, such as astrometry, are in this sense purely astronomy rather than also astrophysics.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Research departments may use "astronomy" and "astrophysics" according to whether the department is historically affiliated with a physics department, and many professional astronomers have physics rather than astronomy degrees.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Thus, in modern use, the two terms are often used interchangeably.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The initial development of astronomy was driven by practical needs like agricultural calendars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Before recorded history archeological sites such as Stonehenge provide evidence of ancient interest in astronomical observations.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Evidence also comes from artefacts such as the Nebra sky disc inlaid with symbols interpreted as a sun, moon, and stars including a cluster of seven stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Megalithic structures located in Nabta Playa, Upper Egypt featured astronomical calendar arrangements in alignment with the heliacal rising of Sirius and supported calibration the yearly calendar for the annual Nile flood.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Civilizations such as Egypt, Mesopotamia, Greece, India, China independently but with cross-cultural influences created astronomical observatories and developed ideas on the nature of the Universe, along with calendars and astronomical instruments.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] A key early development was the beginning of mathematical and scientific astronomy among the Babylonians, laying the foundations for astronomical traditions in other civilizations.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The Babylonians discovered that lunar eclipses recurred in the saros cycle of 223 synodic months.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Following the Babylonians, significant advances were made in ancient Greece and the Hellenistic world.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Greek astronomy sought a rational, physical explanation for celestial phenomena.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the 4th century BC, Heracleides Ponticus was the first to proposed that the Earth rotates on its own axis.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the 3rd century BC, Aristarchus of Samos estimated the size and distance of the Moon and Sun, and he proposed a model of the Solar System where the Earth and planets rotated around the Sun, now called the heliocentric model.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the 2nd century BC, Hipparchus calculated the size and distance of the Moon and invented the earliest known astronomical devices such as the astrolabe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] He also observed the small drift in the positions of the equinoxes and solstices with respect to the fixed stars that we now know is caused by precession.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Hipparchus also created a catalog of 1020 stars, and most of the constellations of the northern hemisphere derive from Greek astronomy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] 150–80 BC) was an early analog computer designed to calculate the location of the Sun, Moon, and planets for a given date.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Technological artifacts of similar complexity did not reappear until the 14th century, when mechanical astronomical clocks appeared in Europe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] After the classical Greek era, astronomy was dominated by the geocentric model of the Universe, or the Ptolemaic system, named after Claudius Ptolemy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] His 13-volume astronomy work, named the *Almagest* in its Arabic translation, became the primary reference for over a thousand years.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In this system, the Earth was believed to be the center of the Universe with the Sun, the Moon and the stars rotating around it.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] While the system would eventually be discredited, it gave the most accurate predictions for the positions of astronomical bodies available at that time.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] With the arrival of Hellenistic astronomy in India through trade and cultural contacts, Indian astronomy entered a new phase during the early centuries CE.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the later medieval period, the Kerala school contributed to astronomy through refined observational practices and more accurate planetary and eclipse calculations.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy flourished in the medieval Islamic world.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomical observatories were established there by the early 9th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 964, the Andromeda Galaxy, the largest galaxy in the Local Group, was described by the Persian Muslim astronomer Abd al-Rahman al-Sufi in his *Book of Fixed Stars*.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The SN 1006 supernova, the brightest apparent magnitude stellar event in the last 1000 years, was observed by the Egyptian Arabic astronomer Ali ibn Ridwan and Chinese astronomers in 1006.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Iranian scholar Al-Biruni observed that, contrary to Ptolemy, the Sun's apogee (highest point in the heavens) was mobile, not fixed.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Arabic astronomers introduced many Arabic names now used for individual stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The ruins at Great Zimbabwe and Timbuktu may have housed astronomical observatories.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In Post-classical West Africa, astronomers studied the movement of stars and relation to seasons, crafting charts of the heavens and diagrams of orbits of the other planets based on complex mathematical calculations.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Songhai historian Mahmud Kati documented a meteor shower in 1583.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Nicole Oresme (1320–1382) discussed evidence for the rotation of the Earth.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Jean Buridan (1300–1361) developed the theory of impetus, describing motions including of the celestial bodies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] For over six centuries (from the recovery of ancient learning during the late Middle Ages into the Enlightenment), the Roman Catholic Church gave more financial and social support to the study of astronomy than probably all other institutions.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Among the Church's motives was finding the date for Easter.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] During the Renaissance, Nicolaus Copernicus proposed a heliocentric model of the solar system.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] While his model maintained circular orbits, it was sufficient to calculate the size of planetary orbits and their period.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The appealing simplicity of Copernican astronomy led to its adoption among astronomers even before it was confirmed by Galileo's telescopic observations in the 1600s.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Sometime around 1608 the telescope was invented and by 1610, Galileo Galilei observed phases on the planet Venus similar to those of the Moon, supporting the heliocentric model.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Around the same time the heliocentric model was organized quantitatively by Johannes Kepler.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Analyzing two decades of careful observations by Tycho Brahe, Kepler devised a system that described the details of the motion of the planets around the Sun.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] While Kepler discarded the uniform circular motion of Copernicus in favor of elliptical motion, he did not succeed in formulating a theory behind the laws he wrote down.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] It was Isaac Newton, with his invention of celestial dynamics and his law of gravitation, who finally explained the motions of the planets.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Newton also developed the reflecting telescope.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Newton, in collaboration with Richard Bentley proposed that stars are like the Sun only much further away.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The new telescopes also altered ideas about stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] By 1610 Galileo discovered that the band of light crossing the sky at night that we call the Milky Way was composed of numerous stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1668 James Gregory compared the luminosity of Jupiter to Sirius to estimate its distance at over 83,000 AU.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The English astronomer John Flamsteed, Britain's first Astronomer Royal, catalogued over 3000 stars but the data were published against his wishes in 1712.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The astronomer William Herschel made a detailed catalog of nebulosity and clusters, and in 1781 discovered the planet Uranus, the first new planet found.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Friedrich Bessel developed the technique of stellar parallax in 1838 but it was so difficult to apply that only about 100 stars were measured by 1900.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] During the 18–19th centuries, the study of the three-body problem by Leonhard Euler, Alexis Claude Clairaut, and Jean le Rond d'Alembert led to more accurate predictions about the motions of the Moon and planets.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] This work was further refined by Joseph-Louis Lagrange and Pierre Simon Laplace, allowing the masses of the planets and moons to be estimated from their perturbations.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Significant advances in astronomy came about with the introduction of new technology, including the spectroscope and astrophotography.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1814–15, Joseph von Fraunhofer discovered some 574 dark lines in the spectrum of the sun and of other stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1859, Gustav Kirchhoff ascribed these lines to the presence of different elements.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the late 1700s William Herschel mapped the distribution of stars in different directions from Earth, concluding that the universe consisted of the Sun near the center of disk of stars, the Milky Way.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] After John Michell demonstrated that stars differ in intrinsic luminosity and after Herschel's own observations with more powerful telescopes that additional stars appeared in all directions, astronomers began to consider that some of the fuzzy spiral nebulae were distant *island Universes*.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The existence of galaxies, including the Earth's galaxy, the Milky Way, as a group of stars was only demonstrated in the 20th century.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1912, Henrietta Leavitt discovered Cepheid variable stars with well-defined, periodic luminosity changes which can be used to fix the star's true luminosity which then becomes an accurate tool for distance estimates.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Using Cepheid variable stars, Harlow Shapley constructed the first accurate map of the Milky Way.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Using the Hooker Telescope, Edwin Hubble identified Cepheid variables in several spiral nebulae and in 1922–1923 proved conclusively that Andromeda Nebula and Triangulum among others, were entire galaxies outside our own, thus proving that the universe consists of a multitude of galaxies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Albert Einstein's 1917 publication of general relativity began the modern era of theoretical models of the universe as a whole.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1922, Alexander Friedman published simplified models for the universe showing static, expanding and contracting solutions.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In 1929 Hubble published observations that the galaxies are all moving away from Earth with a velocity proportional to distance, a relation now known as Hubble's law.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] This relation is expected if the universe is expanding.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The consequence that the universe was once very dense and hot, a Big Bang concept expounded by Georges Lemaître in 1927, was discussed but no experimental evidence was available to support it.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] From the 1940s on, nuclear reaction rates under high density conditions were studied leading to the development of a successful model of big bang nucleosynthesis in the late 1940s and early 1950s.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Then in 1965 cosmic microwave background radiation was discovered, cementing the evidence for the Big Bang.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astrophysics predicted the existence of objects such as black holes and neutron stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] These have been used to explain phenomena such as quasars and pulsars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Space telescopes have enabled measurements in parts of the electromagnetic spectrum normally blocked or blurred by the atmosphere.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The LIGO project detected evidence of gravitational waves in 2015.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Observational astronomy relies on many different wavelengths of electromagnetic radiation and the forms of astronomy are categorized according to the corresponding region of the electromagnetic spectrum on which the observations are made.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Specific information on these subfields is given below.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Radio astronomy uses radiation with long wavelengths, mainly between 1 millimeter and 15 meters (frequencies from 20 MHz to 300 GHz), far outside the visible range.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Hydrogen, otherwise an invisible gas, produces a spectral line at 21 cm (1420 MHz) which is observable at radio wavelengths.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Objects observable at radio wavelengths include interstellar gas, pulsars, fast radio bursts, supernovae, and active galactic nuclei.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Infrared astronomy detects infrared radiation with wavelengths longer than red visible light, outside the range of our vision.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The infrared spectrum is useful for studying objects that are too cold to radiate visible light, such as planets, circumstellar disks or nebulae whose light is blocked by dust.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The longer wavelengths of infrared can penetrate clouds of dust that block visible light, allowing the observation of young stars embedded in molecular clouds and the cores of galaxies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Observations from the Wide-field Infrared Survey Explorer (WISE) have been particularly effective at unveiling numerous galactic protostars and their host star clusters.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] With the exception of infrared wavelengths close to visible light, such radiation is heavily absorbed by the atmosphere, or masked, as the atmosphere itself produces significant infrared emission.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Consequently, infrared observatories have to be located in high, dry places on Earth or in space.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Some molecules radiate strongly in the infrared.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] This allows the study of the chemistry of space.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The James Webb Space Telescope senses infrared radiation to detect very distant galaxies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Visible light from these galaxies was emitted billions of years ago and the expansion of the universe shifted the light in to the infrared range.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] By studying these distant galaxies astronomers hope to learn about the formation of the first galaxies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Historically, optical astronomy, which has been also called visible light astronomy, is the oldest form of astronomy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Images of observations were originally drawn by hand.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the late 19th century and most of the 20th century, images were made using photographic equipment.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Modern images are made using digital detectors, particularly using charge-coupled devices (CCDs) and recorded on modern medium.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Although visible light itself extends from approximately 380 to 700 nm that same equipment can be used to observe some near-ultraviolet and near-infrared radiation.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Ultraviolet astronomy employs ultraviolet wavelengths which are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere, requiring observations from the upper atmosphere or from space.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Ultraviolet astronomy is best suited to the study of thermal radiation and spectral emission lines from hot blue OB stars that are very bright at these wavelengths.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] X-ray astronomy uses X-radiation, produced by extremely hot and high-energy processes.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Since X-rays are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere, observations must be performed at high altitude, such as from balloons, rockets, or specialized satellites.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] X-ray sources include X-ray binaries, supernova remnants, clusters of galaxies, and active galactic nuclei.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Since the Sun's surface is relatively cool, X-ray images of the Sun and other stars give valuable information on the hot solar corona.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Gamma ray astronomy observes astronomical objects at the shortest wavelengths (highest energy) of the electromagnetic spectrum.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Gamma rays may be observed directly by satellites such as the Compton Gamma Ray Observatory, or by specialized telescopes called atmospheric Cherenkov telescopes.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Cherenkov telescopes do not detect the gamma rays directly but instead detect the flashes of visible light produced when gamma rays are absorbed by the Earth's atmosphere.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Gamma-ray astronomy provides information on the origin of cosmic rays, possible annihilation events for dark matter, relativistic particles outflows from active galactic nuclei (AGN), and, using AGN as distant sources, properties of intergalactic space.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Gamma-ray bursts, which radiate transiently, are extremely energetic events, and are the brightest (most luminous) phenomena in the universe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Some events originating from great distances may be observed from the Earth using systems that do not rely on electromagnetic radiation.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In neutrino astronomy, astronomers use heavily shielded underground facilities such as SAGE, GALLEX, and Kamioka II/III for the detection of neutrinos.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The vast majority of the neutrinos streaming through the Earth originate from the Sun, but 24 neutrinos were also detected from supernova 1987A.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Cosmic rays, which consist of very high energy particles (atomic nuclei) that can decay or be absorbed when they enter the Earth's atmosphere, result in a cascade of secondary particles which can be detected by current observatories.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Gravitational-wave astronomy employs gravitational-wave detectors to collect observational data about distant massive objects.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] A few observatories have been constructed, such as the *Laser Interferometer Gravitational Observatory* LIGO.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] LIGO made its first detection on 14 September 2015, observing gravitational waves from a binary black hole.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] A second gravitational wave was detected on 26 December 2015 and additional observations should continue but gravitational waves require extremely sensitive instruments.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The combination of observations made using electromagnetic radiation, neutrinos or gravitational waves and other complementary information, is known as multi-messenger astronomy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] One of the oldest fields in astronomy, and in all of science, is the measurement of the positions of celestial objects known as astrometry.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Historically, accurate knowledge of the positions of the Sun, Moon, planets and stars has been essential in celestial navigation (the use of celestial objects to guide navigation) and in the making of calendars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Careful measurement of the positions of the planets has led to a solid understanding of gravitational perturbations, and an ability to determine past and future positions of the planets with great accuracy, a field known as celestial mechanics.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The measurement of stellar parallax of nearby stars provides a fundamental baseline in the cosmic distance ladder that is used to measure the scale of the Universe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Parallax measurements of nearby stars provide an absolute baseline for the properties of more distant stars, as their properties can be compared.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Measurements of the radial velocity and proper motion of stars allow astronomers to plot the movement of these systems through the Milky Way galaxy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Physical cosmology, the study of large-scale structure of the Universe, seeks to understand the formation and evolution of the cosmos.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Fundamental to modern cosmology is the well-accepted theory of the Big Bang, the concept that the universe begin extremely dense and hot, then expanded over the course of 13.8 billion years to its present condition.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The concept of the Big Bang became widely accepted after the discovery of the microwave background radiation in 1965.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Dark matter and dark energy are now thought form 96% of the mass of the Universe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] For this reason, much effort is expended in trying to understand the physics of these components.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The study of objects outside our galaxy is concerned with the formation and evolution of galaxies, their morphology (description) and classification, the observation of active galaxies, and at a larger scale, the groups and clusters of galaxies.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] These assist the understanding of the large-scale structure of the cosmos.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Galactic astronomy studies galaxies including the Milky Way, a barred spiral galaxy that is a prominent member of the Local Group of galaxies and contains the Solar System.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] It is a rotating mass of gas, dust, stars and other objects, held together by mutual gravitational attraction.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] As the Earth is within the dusty outer arms, large portions of the Milky Way are obscured from view.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Kinematic studies of matter in the Milky Way and other galaxies show there is more mass than can be accounted for by visible matter.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] A dark matter halo appears to dominate the mass, although the nature of this dark matter remains undetermined.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The study of stars and stellar evolution is fundamental to our understanding of the Universe.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The astrophysics of stars has been determined through observation and theoretical understanding; and from computer simulations of the interior.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Aspects studied include star formation in giant molecular clouds; the formation of protostars; and the transition to nuclear fusion and main-sequence stars, carrying out nucleosynthesis.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Further processes studied include stellar evolution, ending either with supernovae or white dwarfs.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The ejection of the outer layers forms a planetary nebula.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The remnant of a supernova is a dense neutron star, or, if the stellar mass was at least three times that of the Sun, a black hole.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Solar astronomy is the study of the Sun, a typical main-sequence dwarf star of stellar class G2 V, and about 4.6 billion years (Gyr) old.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Processes studied by the science include the sunspot cycle, the sun's changes in luminosity, both steady and periodic, and the behavior of the sun's various layers, namely its core with its nuclear fusion, the radiation zone, the convection zone, the photosphere, the chromosphere, and the corona.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Planetary science is the study of the assemblage of planets, moons, dwarf planets, comets, asteroids, and other bodies orbiting the Sun, as well as exoplanets orbiting distant stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The Solar System has been relatively well-studied, initially through telescopes and then later by spacecraft.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Processes studied include planetary differentiation; the generation of, and effects created by, a planetary magnetic field; and the creation of heat within a planet, such as by collisions, radioactive decay, and tidal heating.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In turn, that heat can drive geologic processes such as volcanism, tectonics, and surface erosion, studied by branches of geology.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astrochemistry is an overlap of astronomy and chemistry.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] It studies the abundance and reactions of molecules in the Universe, and their interaction with radiation.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The word "astrochemistry" may be applied to both the Solar System and the interstellar medium.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Studies in this field contribute for example to the understanding of the formation of the Solar System.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astrobiology (or exobiology) studies the origin of life and its development other than on earth.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] It considers whether extraterrestrial life exists, and how humans can detect it if it does.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] It makes use of astronomy, biochemistry, geology, microbiology, physics, and planetary science to investigate the possibility of life on other worlds and help recognize biospheres that might be different from that on Earth.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The origin and early evolution of life is an inseparable part of the discipline of astrobiology.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy and astrophysics have developed interdisciplinary links with other major scientific fields.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Archaeoastronomy is the study of ancient or traditional astronomies in their cultural context, using archaeological and anthropological evidence.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astrostatistics is the application of statistics to the analysis of large quantities of observational astrophysical data.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] As "forensic astronomy", finally, methods from astronomy have been used to solve problems of art history and occasionally of law.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy is one of the sciences to which amateurs can contribute the most.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Collectively, amateur astronomers observe celestial objects and phenomena, sometimes with consumer-level equipment or equipment that they build themselves.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Common targets include the Sun, the Moon, planets, stars, comets, meteor showers, and deep-sky objects such as star clusters, galaxies, and nebulae.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Astronomy clubs throughout the world have programs to help their members set up and run observational programs such as to observe all the objects in the Messier (110 objects) or Herschel 400 catalogues.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Most amateurs work at visible wavelengths, but some have experimented with wavelengths outside the visible spectrum.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] The pioneer of amateur radio astronomy, Karl Jansky, discovered a radio source at the centre of the Milky Way.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Some amateur astronomers use homemade telescopes or radio telescopes originally built for astronomy research (*e.g.* the One-Mile Telescope).
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Amateurs can make occultation measurements to refine the orbits of minor planets.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] They can discover comets, and perform regular observations of variable stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Improvements in digital technology have allowed amateurs to make advances in astrophotography.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] In the 21st century, there remain important unanswered questions in astronomy.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Some are cosmic in scope: for example, what are the dark matter and dark energy that dominate the evolution and fate of the cosmos?
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] What will be the ultimate fate of the universe?
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Why is the abundance of lithium in the cosmos four times lower than predicted by the standard Big Bang model?
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Others pertain to more specific classes of phenomena.
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] For example, is the Solar System normal or atypical?
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] What is the origin of the stellar mass spectrum, i.e. why do astronomers observe the same distribution of stellar masses—the initial mass function—regardless of initial conditions?
[src:dudley-observatory/astronomy] Likewise, questions remain about the formation of the first galaxies, the origin of supermassive black holes, the source of ultra-high-energy cosmic rays, and whether there is other life in the Universe, especially other intelligent life.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He was born in Boston, Massachusetts, the son of Lucretia Dana (Goddard) and Benjamin Apthorp Gould, the principal of Boston Latin School, which the younger Gould attended.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The poet Hannah Flagg Gould was his aunt.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied at Harvard College under Benjamin Peirce, graduating in 1844.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He studied mathematics and astronomy under C.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gauss at Göttingen, Germany, during which time he published approximately 20 papers on the observation and motion of comets and asteroids.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] (he was the first American to receive this degree in astronomy) he toured European observatories asking for advice on what could be done to further astronomy as a professional science in the U.S.A.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The main advice he received was to start a professional journal modeled after what was then the world's leading astronomical publication, the *Astronomische Nachrichten*.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould returned to America in 1848 and from 1852 to 1867 worked in the United States Coast Survey, where he worked in geodetic astronomy and was in charge of the longitude department.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He developed and organized the service, was one of the first to determine longitudes by telegraphic means, and employed the Atlantic cable in 1866 to establish accurate longitude-relations between Europe and America.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] One of his assistants and life-long mentee was Seth Carlo Chandler, who went on to discover the Chandler wobble.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] After his return to Cambridge, Massachusetts, Gould started the *Astronomical Journal* in 1849, which he published until 1861.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He resumed publication in 1885 and it is still published today.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] From 1855 to 1859 he acted as director of the Dudley Observatory at Albany, New York, and in 1859 published a discussion of the places and proper motions of circumpolar stars to be used as standards by the United States Coast Survey.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1861 he undertook the enormous task of preparing for publication the records of astronomical observations made at the United States Naval Observatory since 1850.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1851 Gould suggested numbering asteroids in their order of discovery, and placing this number in a disk (circle) as the generic symbol of an asteroid.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] That same year, he was elected as a member to the American Philosophical Society.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he was admitted to the Massachusetts Society of the Cincinnati to represent his grandfather Captain Benjamin Gould.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In the 1890s he became an early member of the Massachusetts Society of the Sons of the American Revolution.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Appointed in 1862 actuary to the United States Sanitary Commission, he issued in 1869 an important volume of *Investigations in the Military and Anthropological Statistics of American Soldiers*.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] This study, informed by Gould's commitment to race science, purported to construct typologies of Black and Indigenous bodies, in particular.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1864 he fitted up a private observatory at Cambridge, Massachusetts, and undertook in 1868, on behalf of the Argentine republic, to organize a national observatory at Córdoba.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1871 he became the first director of the Argentine National Observatory (today, Observatorio Astronómico de Córdoba of the National University of Córdoba).
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] While there, he and four assistants (including Miles Rock) extensively mapped the southern hemisphere skies using newly developed photometric methods.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] On June 1, 1884, he made the last definite sighting of the Great Comet of 1882.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The need of astronomers for good weather prediction spurred Gould to collaborate with Argentine colleagues to develop the Argentine National Weather Service, the first in South America.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Rutherfurd's photographs of the Pleiades in 1866 entitle him to rank as a pioneer in the use of the camera as an instrument of precision; and he secured at Córdoba 1400 negatives of southern star clusters, the reduction of which occupied the closing years of his life.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He remained in Argentina until 1885, when he returned to Cambridge, Massachusetts.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He received the Gold Medal of the Royal Astronomical Society in 1883 and the James Craig Watson Medal in 1887.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Astronomers continue to investigate the astrophysics of a large scale feature of the Milky Way to which he called their attention in 1877, and honor him with its name, The Gould Belt.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] A crater on the Moon is named after him.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould was elected a member of the American Antiquarian Society in 1892.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] He died at Cambridge, Massachusetts in 1896.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] In 1874, while in Argentina with his assistants, Gould completed his greatest work, the *Uranometria Argentina*, consisting of an atlas published in 1877 and catalog in 1879, for which he received in 1883 the gold medal of the Royal Astronomical Society.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The atlas introduced the system of defining constellation boundaries along lines of right ascension and declination, which was officially adopted by the International Astronomical Union for the whole sky in 1930.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] The catalog assigned Gould designations to all bright stars within 100 degrees of the south celestial pole in a manner similar to what Flamsteed had earlier done for the northern hemisphere.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] An updated version, to which late 20th century data have been appended to the complete information for all stars in the original Uranometria Argentina, is available at www.uranometriaargentina.com/.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Gould followed his *Uranometria Argentina* with a zone-catalogue of 73,160 stars (1884), and a general catalogue (1885) compiled from meridian observations of 32,448 stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-apthorp-gould] Alice Bache Gould (1868–1953), a mathematician, philanthropist, and historian, was one of his five children.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] Boss was born in Albany, New York to astronomer Lewis Boss and Helen M.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] After attending The Albany Academy, he graduated from Harvard University in 1901 and worked at Dudley Observatory until 1905.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] Naval Observatory in Washington, D.C., he became director of the U.S.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] Naval Observatory at Samoa and helped organized the expedition to Flint Island to observe the 1908 solar eclipse.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] He served as director from 1906 to 1908.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] He joined the Department of Meridian Astrometry of the Carnegie Institution of Washington in 1908, working as a secretary until 1912 when he became acting director.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] In 1915, he became director of the department.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] He also served as director of Dudley Observatory from 1912 to 1956.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] His primary work was in positional astronomy, particularly in the positions and motions of the stars.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] His father served as editor of the *Astronomical Journal* from 1909 until his death 1912, whereupon Benjamin undertook the duty until 1941.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] In 1936 his *General Catalogue of 33,342 Stars* was published by the Carnegie Institution of Washington, DC.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] This publication replaced the *Preliminary General Catalogue of 6,188 stars* of Lewis Boss, and it became known as the *Boss General Catalogue*.
[src:dudley-observatory/benjamin-boss] Boss died on October 17, 1970, in Albany, New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] The hospital occupies a site on New Scotland Avenue that previously housed the Bender Laboratory and the Dudley Observatory.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] The observatory's building was vacated in the late 1960s when the institution moved to a different location; after a 1970 fire, the structure was demolished and Capital District Psychiatric Center was constructed on the former observatory site circa 1972.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] In 1975, William DeVita opened a small variety store at CDPC as a not-for-profit corporation employing people with psychiatric disabilities; the project evolved into Rehabilitation Support Services, an organization that provides housing and rehabilitation programs across upstate New York.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] In 2025, the New York State Division of the Budget and mental health advocacy organizations highlighted funding for an eight-bed acute care crisis unit and expanded mobile integration services, as well as staffing and infrastructure improvements at the facility.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] In 2025, Governor Kathy Hochul's office reported that ten additional adult psychiatric beds had been opened at CDPC as part of a broader plan to restore inpatient psychiatric capacity at state-operated facilities.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] CDPC provides inpatient psychiatric treatment and rehabilitation for adults diagnosed with persistent mental illness, particularly individuals who have not responded to short-term treatment in general hospital psychiatric units.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] The facility operates adult inpatient units as well as outpatient services including an Albany outpatient clinic, a child and adolescent outpatient clinic, and community-based crisis services.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] CDPC's programs include a crisis intervention unit and crisis inpatient beds, mobile integration teams, and community residential programs such as the New Scotland Residence, which supports individuals transitioning from inpatient care to community living.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] As of 2025, the facility hosts 100 beds, 294 annual admissions, and 48 outpatient visits.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] The center is located on a medical campus that includes Albany Medical Center, the Albany College of Pharmacy and Health Sciences, Albany Law School, the Stratton Veterans Affairs Medical Center and the OMH central office complex.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] A neighboring tertiary-care hospital also provides treatment.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] CDPC has been discussed in case law and legal scholarship concerning involuntary commitment, patient rights and seclusion practices.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] New York appellate decisions such as *Christine Q.Q. v.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] Psychiatric Center* (1985), *Matter of Stephen W.* (2011) and *Matter of Howard U.* (2017) have addressed issues including standards for retaining patients for continued inpatient psychiatric care and the evidentiary threshold for involuntary hospitalization.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] Incidents in 2012 and 2016 prompted concerns about patient seclusion policy and workplace safety.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] CDPC appeared in media coverage of criminal cases and the insanity defense.
[src:dudley-observatory/capital-district-psychiatric-center] The PBS *Frontline* documentary *A Case of Insanity* described the role of CDPC in evaluating and treating Ralph Tortorici, a defendant whose case raised questions about competency, criminal responsibility and the treatment of severe mental illness in the criminal justice system.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The Observatory was chartered on February 11, 1852, by the New York State Senate, and by the New York State Assembly on April 3, 1852.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Dudley of Albany, a former United States Senator and member of the Albany Regency.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Dudley lived in New York State, died in 1841, and his widow Blandina Bleeker Dudley endowed the Dudley Observatory after his death.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Dudley Observatory has operated from at least six separate sites since its founding.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The first location of the observatory was on a rise to the north-east of downtown Albany that was locally known as "Goat Hill".
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Today, that location is the approximate location of Arbor Hill Elementary School.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Construction began in 1852 and the building was dedicated on August 28, 1856, prior to its completion, with Edward Everett, former President of Harvard University and United States Secretary of State delivering the keynote oration.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Dudley was one of the original founding institutions comprising Union University when it was founded on April 10, 1873, by an act of the New York State Legislature.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] By the 1890s, railroad traffic around the original building had grown to the point where the vibrations were disrupting the astronomical instruments.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The original building was sold to the city of Albany, and new property was purchased on the grounds of the Albany Alms-House.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] After World War II, Dudley began a transition from astronomical observation to research for the space race.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Consequently, the second observatory was sold to Albany Medical Center in 1963.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The building burned down in 1970 and was replaced by the Capital District Psychiatric Center.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] After the sale of the second observatory, an office building was purchased at 100 Fuller Road, near the University at Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] This phase lasted until the end of the space race, when funding from NASA dried up.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The Fuller Road office was rented to the University in 1976.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] After briefly being located in a strip mall in Latham, New York, the observatory donated its rare book collection to the Union College Library.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] From there it moved to a house on Union Avenue in 1977, before moving to the Schaffer Heights Senior Apartments building at 107 Nott Terrace in Schenectady, remaining in the latter location until 2015.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] In 2008, they refurbished their circa 1893 Pruyn telescope.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] Recently, the observatory has evolved from a research facility to an educational foundation.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] In 2015 in moved to the Museum of Innovation and Science in Schenectady.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] In 2018, ground was broken for an observatory located on the grounds of the museum which would have marked the first time Dudley would serve as a working observatory in almost 40 years.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] In 2019, the Dudley Observatory moved to the grounds of Siena University in Loudonville, N.Y.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] At the same time, the archival collection was donated to the New York State Archives, which had the resources to catalog and preserve the Observatory's documents.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] A collection of scientific hardware, including a Brashear refracting telescope and equatorial mount, were donated to the New York State Museum in Albany.
[src:dudley-observatory/dudley-observatory] The Dudley Observatory maintains a collection of rare books including first editions by Galileo and Copernicus.
